About the project

Our era of data - larger than ever and complex like chaos - requires several skills from statisticians and other data scientists. We must discover the patterns hidden behind numbers in matrices and arrays. We are not afraid of coding, recoding, programming, or modelling. We want to visualize, analyze, interpret, understand, and communicate. These are the core themes of Open Data Science (Open Data - Open Science - Data Science). And this course is THE course for learning these skills.

Link to my IODS Github repository

Fitting a regression model

Lets try to model points with 3 variables. I choose age, attitude and stra.

model1 <- lm(points ~ age + attitude + stra, data = lrn14)
summary(model1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ age + attitude + stra, data = lrn14)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -18.1149  -3.2003   0.3303   3.4129  10.7599 
## 
## Coefficients:

## (Intercept) 10.89543    2.64834   4.114 6.17e-05 ***

## 
## Residual standard error: 5.26 on 162 degrees of freedom

## F-statistic: 15.07 on 3 and 162 DF,  p-value: 1.07e-08

Only attitude seems to be correlated enough (other are P<0.1, attitude p<0.001), so lets dump the other two from the model.

model2 <- lm(points ~ attitude , data = lrn14)
summary(model2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude, data = lrn14)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max

## attitude      3.5255     0.5674   6.214 4.12e-09 ***

## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.32 on 164 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1906, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1856 
## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

Attitude is a statistically significant variable.

Lets visualize the model.

qplot(attitude, points, data = lrn14) + geom_smooth(method = "lm")

Model diagnostics

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(model2, which = c(1,2,5))

Our model seems to be valid.

Conclusion

Positive attitude gives you more points!
